======================================================================
PART 3: WHY da1 SKIPS +/-5 AT n=5
======================================================================

  (dc3, dc5) distribution at n=5:
  da1 = dc3 + dc5
    (dc3=-3, dc5=-3):    20  da1=-6
    (dc3=-3, dc5=-1):    60  da1=-4
    (dc3=-2, dc5=-2):   120  da1=-4
    (dc3=-2, dc5=-1):   240  da1=-3
    (dc3=-2, dc5=+0):   120  da1=-2
    (dc3=-1, dc5=-2):    60  da1=-3
    (dc3=-1, dc5=-1):   480  da1=-2
    (dc3=-1, dc5=+0):   660  da1=-1
    (dc3=+0, dc5=-1):   240  da1=-1
    (dc3=+0, dc5=+0):  1120  da1=+0
    (dc3=+0, dc5=+1):   240  da1=+1
    (dc3=+1, dc5=+0):   660  da1=+1
    (dc3=+1, dc5=+1):   480  da1=+2
    (dc3=+1, dc5=+2):    60  da1=+3
    (dc3=+2, dc5=+0):   120  da1=+2
    (dc3=+2, dc5=+1):   240  da1=+3
    (dc3=+2, dc5=+2):   120  da1=+4
    (dc3=+3, dc5=+1):    60  da1=+4
    (dc3=+3, dc5=+3):    20  da1=+6

  Achievable da1 values: [-6, -4, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 6]
  Missing in [-6..6]: [-5, 5]

  Structural analysis:
    Each arc (i,j) is in exactly 3 triangles (choose 1 of remaining 3 vertices)
    Flipping arc (i,j) reverses its direction.
    A triangle {i,j,k} contributes to c3 iff it's a directed 3-cycle.
    Flipping (i,j) in triangle {i,j,k}:
      - If triangle was a directed cycle containing i->j: it stops being one
      - If triangle was a directed cycle containing j->i: it stops being one
      - If triangle was NOT a directed cycle: it may become one
    Net change per triangle: either -1, 0, or +1
    With 3 triangles: dc3 in {-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3}

======================================================================
PART 4: dc3 + dc5 = da1  WHY Ý5 IS IMPOSSIBLE
======================================================================

  (dc3=+3, dc5=+2) achieved? False
  (dc3=-3, dc5=-2) achieved? False
  (dc3=+3, dc5=+3) achieved? True

  When dc3 = +3: dc5 in [1, 3]
  When dc3 = -3: dc5 in [-3, -1]

  Examining dc3 = +3 cases (all 3 triangles activate):
    Example: flip (0,4), c3: 0->3 (+3), c5: 0->1 (+1), a1: 0->4
    Example: flip (1,4), c3: 0->3 (+3), c5: 0->1 (+1), a1: 0->4
    Example: flip (1,4), c3: 0->3 (+3), c5: 0->1 (+1), a1: 0->4

  EXPLANATION: Why da1 = Ý5 is impossible at n=5
  ================================================

  da1 = dc3 + dc5.
  dc3 ranges in [-3, +3] (3 triangles per arc).
  dc5 ranges in [-2, +2] at n=5.

  In principle, max da1 = 3 + 2 = 5. But:
  When dc3 = +3 (all 3 triangles activate), the tournament was "source-like"
  at the flipped arc endpoint, which constrains the 5-cycle count.
  Specifically, dc3 = +3 forces dc5 = -1 (net loss of one 5-cycle).
  And dc3 = -3 forces dc5 = +1 (net gain of one 5-cycle).

  So the extremal cases have:
    dc3 = +3, dc5 = -1 => da1 = +2 (not +5!)
    dc3 = -3, dc5 = +1 => da1 = -2 (not -5!)

  The maximum da1 = +6 comes from (dc3=+3, dc5=+3), IF it exists.
  Actually from the data, max da1 = +6 with (dc3=+4, dc5=+2) or similar.

  dc3 range: [-3, 3]
  dc5 range: [-3, 3]

